HI, 
I installed bootstrap 5.2 through npm and the basic functionality worked as expected regarding ScrollSpy as before.  However, I am not able to get the smooth scroll to work (see bug report: https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap/issues/36372). 

Regarding [history.pushState()], please consider the following:

Updating URL without page refresh:
[history.pushState()] has been suggested as a way to append the website URL with the section id as one is scrolling similar to how clicking on the menu works. Right now, with ScrollSpy, the URL only changes for a section when the menu is clicked not when one has scrolled to it, at least with my site. 

Currently no recorded browser history with ScrollSpy:
When scrolling there is no recorded history of the id sections the user has visited and thus they can't use the browser forward and backward arrows to go back to the sections they have scrolled to or to return from them.  In addition, without changes in the page URL, users can’t bookmark or share particular sections if they had scrolled to get there. Ideally, ScrollSpy should provide similar history/URL features as clicking on a menu link. Long website pages are now common in part because scrolling on mobile devices is generally more convenient than clicking to every section.

“One of the most common problems with long scrolling is that sharing a URL to a particular spot on the page is impossible: The user’s scroll position isn’t reflected in the URL, and the URL leads to the top of the page. The user will become easily frustrated when they can’t easily switch between devices to continue browsing from their current spot because the URL doesn’t capture that spot. Starting with HTML5, changing the URL displayed in the browser without reloading the page is possible. The [history.pushState()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/History_API) function enables us to invoke a URL change without reloading the page, thus allowing us to match the scrolling behaviour to the user’s expectation.” 

Currently, URLs changed by clicking on an anchor link stay that way until another anchor link is clicked (e.g., menu). That means that the appended URL may NOT match the section I am visiting if I have navigated through a mixed means of clicking and scrolling. Currently, if I click on the menu to go to a section anchor id and then scroll to a different section, the URL no longer matches the new section I scrolled to. As I said, it would be wonderful if the navigation, URL and history behaviour remained consistent whether scrolling or using a menu to visit an anchored section. 

Here is an example Jquery modification someone suggested on StackOverflow to change the URL on scroll to anchor, with the added feature of removing the appended id when returning to the very top to avoid redundancy since the base website URL already points to the top: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/69817396/change-url-on-scroll-to-anchor-and-then-remove-when-reach-the-top 

I haven't tested it, but perhaps the following snippet taking from the above link may provide some inspiration:

```
// Source: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/30734552/change-url-while-scrolling
// stackoverflow.com/questions/123999/how-to-tell-if-a-dom-element-is-visible-in-the-current-viewport
function isElementInViewport(el) {
    //special bonus for those using jQuery
    if (typeof jQuery === "function" && el instanceof jQuery) {
        el = el[0];
